    <h5><ul>Rat Care</ul></h5>
    <p>Rat care is a very important subject. They may seem like easy pets to maintain, but they have a few very 
    important requirements to keep in mind. So, here's some handy information on rat care.</p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        They're incredibly social animals. Thus, if you're getting ONE rat.... You need to prepare to get more. As friendly as a
        human can be, rats depend on other rats for companionship, grooming, and socializing. Without another rat, they'll
        become anxious. So, at least keep them in same-sex pairs.
      </li>

      <li>
        Rats are intelligent and curious. So, they need a lot of enrichment. You are probably going to need a bigger cage (honestly,
        the bigger the better). Also, don't keep them in glass tanks. Their lungs are sensitive, and the lack of fresh airflow might
        damage their lungs. Do tons of research on toys to make sure they're safe! Things like platforms, hammocks, places to hide,
        and things to chew on are all good bets for things to put in their cage. 
      </li>

      <li>
        Rats may be affectionate and loving, but they'll need time to trust you first! Spend lots of time with them, talk to them,
        anything to get them used to your presence. They'll come to be loving in their own time!
      </li>

      <li>
        A rat isn't a "low maintenance" pet. They're prone to tumors and respiratory issues, and can easily cost a lot of money in
        vet bills for a 2-3 year life span. Don't adopt rats with the expectation of easy pet care. It's time and committment. That
        being said, if you're willing to put in the work, rats make excellent companions!
      </li>
    </ul>

